data.title: #kyuss | vinylspinning
data.text:
Lowrider: Refractions (2019)

I'm not a big proponent of bands reuniting, especially decades after their break-up -- let sleeping dogs lie, say I!

But, sometimes, one of those resurrected groups will prove me wrong, and that was definitely the case with Swedish stoner rockers, Lowrider, who ended a 19-year-hiatus five years ago with their sophomore album, Refractions.

Back in the year 2000, when Lowrider released their full-length debut AND apparent swan song, Ode to Io, the knock on the Swedish quartet was that they sounded just like Kyuss, even though hundreds of bands did too, generally with much poorer results.

But any conceivable statute of limitations for musical inspiration (don't ask a lawyer, I'm making this shit up) had long since expired by the time Lowrider finally reentered our solar system in 2013, after a decade-plus trip through the endless void.

More specifically, that was the year in which the original foursome of Peder Bergstrand (vocals, bass), Ole Hellquist (vocals, lead guitar), Niclas Stlfors (guitar), and Andreas Eriksson (drums) reunited for the 2013 DesertFest in Berlin, Germany.

So, by the time they were coaxed back into the studio by Blues Funeral Recordings, Lowrider had successfully replenished their stores of authentic stoner/desert/space rock -- and then some!

New trips like "Red River," "Sernanders Krog," and eleven-minute epic "Pipe Rider" fluidly shuffle pummeling riffs with rolling grooves, psychedelic leads with mesmerizing melodies, while, across it all, Bergstrand's wounded moan accurately conveys the astronaut's unimaginable loneliness.

"Ode to Ganymede" is a nod to the first album's Jovian Moon theme, and while its alien wah-wah break is pure '90s stoner rock the subsequent Hammond organ solo recalls '70s Deep Purple -- a reminder that no one band "owns" exclusive rights to rock 'n' roll.

And a pair of thoroughly engrossing instrumentals, "Sun Devil/M87*" and "Ol' Mule Pepe," prove just as effective as their voiced counterparts; with the latter's finale crashing to Earth with a force not heard since Acrimony's Tumuli Shroomaroom ... or the asteroid that killed the dinosaurs, take your pick.

Or, to put it as clearly as I possibly can: these are all great, great songs!

Therefore, Refractions is wisely named because, as the included liner notes state, it doesn't exactly reflect the band's past exploits like a mirror would, but refracts it through the prism of time and space into something both familiar and fresh.

In doing so, the album fully validates Lowrider's decision to resume the good work they abandoned all those years ago, with the added benefit of no longer operating under Kyuss' oppressive yoke that assailed them, to begin with.

More Lowrider: Ode to Io.

Abrams: Blue City (2024)

Through little fault of their own, Denver, Colorado's Abrams got off on the wrong foot with me because their moniker challenges AC/DC's fixed and non-negotiable position at the very front of my alphabetically- and chronologically-organized record collection.

I mean, what would possess any band to choose a name starting with the letters 'A' and 'B'?

All kidding aside (note: I'm really NOT kidding), 2024's Blue City is Abrams' fifth long-player since their debut in 2015, and that's evident in the confident wall of sound unleashed by Zachary Amster (vocals, guitar), Taylor Iversen (bass, vocals), Ryan DeWitt (drums), and recent addition Graham Zander (guitar, vocals).

But there's a catch: despite their association with iconic stoner rock labels like Small Stone and, in this case, Blues Funeral, the quartet's, precise, densely layered, interwoven guitars owe just as much to '90s alternative rock, in my opinion.

Expertly recorded and produced by Kurt Ballou (Converge, High On Fire, etc., etc.), typical six-string symphonies like "Fire Waltz," "Wasting Time," and the tectonic title track actually remind me of the Smashing Pumpkins and Hum, as well as Floridian thunder-pop purveyors Torche (who also happen to be Ballou clients).

For their part, the dissonant guitars of "Turn it Off" and "Etherol" mimic Nirvana and Soundgarden, respectively, while "Death Om" and "Narc" integrate space rock textures, but that's frankly about as close as Abrams get to bona fide stoners like Kyuss or Monster Magnet.

All this being said, far more important than these sonic comparisons is the impressively high standards of Abrams' songwriting, which may not innovate much but recycles influences into consistently engaging material that rarely falters from start to finish.

Heck, if I were younger, still consuming a lot of brand-new music (almost impossible to process in today's all-you-can-eat streaming era), and could be bothered to make lists and bold pronouncements, this would probably be an 'Album of the Year' candidate for me!

Not bad for a band whose name I objected to from the outset, but don't worry, I'm not an amoral Alphabet Tyrant ...

Having sampled and confirmed the quality of its alternative/stoner rock, Blue City will simply have to join fellow alphabetical "offenders" like Aardvark, Abattoir, Absent in Body, and Absu in my vinyl shelf no-man's-land between AC/DC and Accept.

Surely, there are worse fates than that!

More Latter-Day Stoner Rock & Alternative Rock: Basks American Hollow, Elbrus Elbrus, Elephant Trees Elephant Tree, Foo Fighters Wasting Light, Gozus The Fury of a Patient Man, House of Broken Promises Using the Useless, My Sleeping Karmas My Sleeping Karma, Queens of the Stone Ages Lullabies to Paralyze, Royal Thunders CVI, Sigiriyas Return to Earth, Snails Feral, Totimoshis Milagrosa, Wo Fats The Black Code, Zen Guerrillas Shadows On the Sun.

Monster Magnet: Monolithic Baby! (2004)

It's been 20 years since Monster Magnet came roaring back -- in my opinion, anyway -- following the relative disappointment of 2000's God Says No, armed with a worthy, hard-hitting follow-up to '98's breakthrough Powertrip in '04's Monolithic Baby!

But the previous few years had been filled with challenges for the '90s stoner/space rock champions, who were dropped by their once-supportive label A&M when it was merged with Interscope and Geffen, its staff (including yours truly) gutted in the process.

Amid the fallout, Magnet's long-serving rhythm section of bassist Joe Calandra and drummer Jon Kleiman also gave notice, leaving band leader Dave Wyndorf with one more headache to solve as he planned his next moves.

But, after securing a new deal from Germany's SPV, Wyndorf recruited bassist Jim Baglino and drummer Bob Pantella (*) to join him, lead guitarist Ed Mundell, and rhythm guitarist Phil Caivano for this new, indie-backed chapter of Monster Magnet's career.

And Monolithic Baby! wasted no time at all proving Dave still had it as a songwriter, blasting off with a lean, mean triple-threat in the comically ambiguous "Slut Machine," the groupie-bashing "Supercruel," and a countdown to ecstasy in "On the Verge."

Next up, "Unbroken (Hotel Baby)" might just be the best, most infectious hard rock single Wyndorf ever wrote (yes, right up there with "Space Lord"), but its chorus -- "Shut your mouth you big fucking baby" -- didn't exactly help its cause at radio.

Not that SPV's promo budget could compare with A&M's, as evidenced by the song's modest U.S. Rock Chart peak of No. 31 vs. the No. 1 achieved by "Space Lord," which incidentally, also had a bleeped F-word to contend with.

Back to the album: more strong material ("Radiation Day," "Monolithic," "Master of Light") precedes a moderate second-half slump ("Too Bad," "Ultimate Everything," "CNN War Theme"), but nothing here undermines the amplifier stack monolith amplifier the band is seen lording over on the cover.

And while this LP has one of the lowest psych-and-space rock quotients in Magnet's discography, they still slam their way through Bob Calvert's (of Hawkwind fame) pounding solo obscurity "The Right Stuff," cover "There's No Way Out of Here" by David Gilmour-produced country rockers Unicorn, and tackle The Velvet Underground's "Venus in in Furs" for a bonus track.

So even though Monolithic Baby! couldn't return Monster Magnet to Powertrip's commercial heyday (I don't know of another Gold-certified stoner rock album), it was still an admirable career re-set that earned them at least two more decades of, as Wyndorf once put it, "kissing the mouth of the scorpion."

* Drums on the album were performed by Michael Wildwood.

Goatsnake: Goatsnake Vol. 1 (1999)

I was ALL IN on '90s stoner rock -- Kyuss, Monster Magnet, Fu Manchu, you name it! -- and, before that, classic doom -- Trouble, Candlemass, Black Fucking Sabbath, etc. -- but Goatsnake barely registered on my radar because, well, how can I put this?

I just didn't think they were very good.

Goatsnake formed in 1996, when the recently disbanded The Obsessed rhythm section of bassist Guy Pinhas and drummer Greg Rogers began jamming with guitarist Greg Anderson, previously of Thorr's Hammer, Burning Witch, and countless other bands.

For their frontman, the trio chose a rather unconventional, certainly unexpected, approach in former Scream and Wool frontman Pete Stahl, then got to work on a couple of 7-inches, the Sabbath-referencing IV and Man of Light -- both issued in 1998.

Now, don't forget that, at the time, Anderson and his frequent partner Stephen O'Malley were only just launching their own influential label, Southern Lord, and their iconic drone project Sunn O))), so Goatsnake was very much Anderson's priority.

But, as I said at the top of this blog, '99's Goatsnake Vol. 1 didn't impress me all that much, and I had no plans to revisit, nor to possibly revise my original opinion, until I found this vinyl reissue at a bargain price.

And, yes, it helped that the album's embarrassing original artwork, featuring a Viking ship sailing under a Confederate Flag (already in bad taste years before these were justifiably canceled), had been replaced by the classy, silver-on-black design seen here.

Note how that the font treatment echoes Sunn O)))'s sound waves ...

Anyway, sorry to keep you in suspense, but I'm afraid that a quarter-century has done little to ameliorate my original assessment of mediocre doom grinds like "IV," "Lord of Los Feliz," "Trower" (the string section was a nice touch, I suppose), and the frankly ridiculous "Dog Catcher."

Along with comparative "highlights" like the moderately galloping "Slippin' the Stealth," the harmonica-enhanced "Innocent," and the all-around very solid "Mower," these tracks ultimately offer nothing beyond serviceable, formulaic, derivative stoner metal.

OK, fine, I'll add a few points to "What Love Remains" because Anderson's sluggish, leviathan riffs point to his way forward with Sunn O))), but I simply don't rate Stahl's brassy, inexpressive vocals very highly -- sorry!

So I better shut the hell up before I piss off some of my stoner rock/doom brethren with this most likely unpopular evaluation; but I'll stand by it and will always recommend dozens of other bands and albums over Goatsnake and their largely disappointing discography.

Queens of the Stone Age: Era Vulgaris (2007)

I still can't decide whether this triple 10-inch format for an album that runs a very conventional 47 minutes is really cool or terribly pretentious, but then, there's a lot I still can't decide about 2007's Era Vulgaris.

What I do know (or think I know, anyway) is that Queens of the Stone Age mastermind Josh Homme decided that a creative pivot was in order for his band's fifth studio LP, after seeing the inventive and eccentric formula of 2000's Rated R and '02's Songs for the Deaf grow stale on 05s Lullabies to Paralyze.

As I wrote in this piece for Loudwire, Era Vulgaris found Homme seeking inspiration in the frustrations of urban living, like the tension of L.A. traffic (hey, whatever works!), to deconstruct the Q.O.T.S.A. sound into shorter, simpler songs with sharper edges.

However, this stylistic transition felt a little jarring to longtime fans like myself (and tellingly galvanized previously indifferent critics -- go figure), who didn't quite know what to make of the mechanical dissonance and nervous twitch of cuts like "I'm Designer," "Misfit Love," and "Battery Acid."

Along with first single "Sick, Sick, Sick," these songs marked a stark and definitive schism from Q.O.T.S.A.'s desert-inspired stoner rock heritage in Kyuss, but they did allow Homme and co. to embrace a cold clinical, almost pseudo-electronic brand of post-new wave.

Oh, of course there were throwbacks, such as the Mark Lanegan-crooned "Into the Hollow," the catchy staccato grooves of "3's & 7's," and the creepy easy-listening of "Suture Up Your Future," all of which my ears gobbled down like so much musical comfort food.

And in the strutting, strolling, falsetto-spiked curiosity, "Make it Wit Chu," the band delivered a Third Millennium update on The Rolling Stones' "Miss You" or "Emotional Rescue," which I previously described as "zombie soul" for reasons I can no longer remember.

Whatever it means, you gotta admit it sounds kind of cool ...

Anyway, due to all of these mixed feelings, Era Vulgaris has never quite won me over, but it has grown on me over time, and I've never denied that Q.O.T.S.A. were ripe for a change, at the time.

Unfortunately, Interscope Records felt differently and subsequently dropped the band, freeing Homme to explore other projects like the supergroup Them Crooked Vultures, the anything-but-super Eagles of Death Metal, and even production work for the Arctic Monkeys.

By the time he reconvened Queens of the Stone Age for 2013's ... Like Clockwork (released, as have been its successors, through indie Matador Records), the group's best work was unquestionably behind them, but they are still sometimes capable of exciting and confounding listeners partial to head-scratching music in equal measures.

Clutch: Blast Tyrant (2004)

Last year I realized that my favorite Clutch LPs bizarrely arrive in nine-year intervals, and I'll take you through them, in reverse order, now: 2022's Sunrise on Slaughter Beach, '13's Earth Rocker, '04's Blast Tyrant, and '95's self-titled sophomore album.

Should I consult a numerologist?

Today, I'm obviously revisiting Blast Tyrant on its 20th anniversary (give or take a day) and since I haven't spun it in almost that many years, the following will combine words from my original All-Music Guide review with a few fresh-ear perspectives.

I'll start with my thesis about how Clutch is one of those rare bands that have prospered for years within a realm of their own devising -- heavy, groovy stoner rock -- with little regard for the music industry's typical career ambitions and monetary concerns.

But I did note that this, the group's sixth long-player (not counting a few EPs and 'odds and sods' sets) was the first in which they replaced analog for digital recording systems -- not that you'd ever know it from the familiarly head-crunching end results.

Anything but, as brand new brain-bashers like "Mercury," "Cypress Grove," "Spleen Merchant," and "Subtle Hustle," with their gruff vocals and punchy, often circular guitar riffs, are still unmistakably Clutch, sonically interchangeable with previous albums.

That's a compliment.

Plus, there's plenty of experimentation and imagination to be found via the snippets of organ and synths, mournful acoustic guitars, and psychy wah-wah brought to bear on "Promoter (Of Earthbound Causes)," "The Regulator," "Ghost," and "La Curandera (Notes from the Trial Of)."

Meanwhile, Neal Fallon's lyrics achieve new heights for topical/comical irony, imagery, and clever puns, particularly on the brilliant "Profits of Doom," "Army of Bono," "The Swollen Goat (In the Wake of The)," and "The Mob Goes Wild, where he incites:

"Everybody, move to Canada right now! Here's how we do it ... Bum-rush the border guard before he and his dog ever knew it.

Streets on fire! The mob goes wild!"

By the end of my AMG review, I'd concluded that Blast Tyrant was quite likely to bewilder those who have previously been bewildered (*), and appease those who were previously appeased, leaving Clutch safely ensconced in that realm of their own creation.

But today that feels like a rather lazy, hurried cop-out of a closing sentence -- not least because Blast Tyrant obviously stands apart and above most other Clutch LPs, alongside the other volumes eligible for my weird nine-year-gap club.

Can't wait for 2031!

* I actually used the word "confound," incorrectly, as it turns out.

The Obsessed: The Church Within (1994)

I confess I was perplexed by The Obsessed's third opus, The Church Within, all of 30 years ago, when I secured my first copy on CD based on Scott 'Wino' Weinrich's laudable track record with Saint Vitus and a rave review in Kerrang! magazine.

Maybe it was the other music I was listening to at the time: a blend of thrash, death, and other extreme metals, the best grunge Seattle had to offer, and random eccentrics ranging from Faith No More, to Kyuss, to King's X, to Frank Zappa.

Note that I blame myself (although the peanut gallery at Encyclopaedia Metallum seems to agree) because I did grow to like (if not love) it, as much as other Wino releases, but I still think the dull, lifeless opener, "To Protect and to Serve," made a terrible first impression.

It's certainly the worst of these 13 tracks (closing instrumental "Living Rain" comes close), which later yielded a clutch of memorable doom grinds ("Blind Lightning," "Streetside," "Mourning"), characterized by Weinrich's unmistakeable gravelly growl and six-string alchemy.

By contrast, our hero's signature detours into hardcore-inspired micro-blasts are notably in short supply here (only "Streamlined" is really worth a damn), but I really like the mid-paced energy of "Touch of Everything."

Another standout (and the album's longest cut), "Neatz Brigade," collects and displays all of Wino's many, disparate talents: thick, hypnotic tones, dissonant power chords, sizzling leads, that haunting voice, plus one of his coolest and weirdest lyrics ...

"The picture that I wanted to see; Were paintings in the wrong museum. The difference between you and me; Is like making love in a mausoleum."

Come to think of it, lyrics might be this album's strongest suit, and I recommend taking the time to review Weinrich's alternately elliptical, cynical, and abstract wordplay on songs like "Field of Hours," "Skybone," and "Climate of Despair."

So there's obviously lots to like (if not love) about The Church Within, and before you start reaching for your pitchforks, remember that the album was a total commercial no-show and The Obsessed dropped just as suddenly as they'd been signed by Columbia.

Not that the major behemoth had any idea how to market an underground doom band, but that was of little help to Wino, who experienced both homelessness and drug addiction over the next few years before resurfacing with his awesome psych/doom vehicle Spirit Caravan.

As for The Obsessed, an 'odds and sods' collection named Incarnate arrived in 1999, and Weinrich finally felt the urge to resurrect the name in 2017, when he recorded Sacred, and I do believe a brand-new album called Gilded Sorrow just landed.

Anyone heard it yet?

The Heads: Mao Tinitus EP (1998)

I hope you are wearing sunglasses ...

The Heads, from Bristol, England, are one of the more prolific and enduring British stoner rock acts (30 years and counting!) but they've sometimes found it difficult to set aside their bongs long enough to record a complete, honest-to-goodness album.

Instead, the band's discography is littered with singles and EPs like this 25-year-old specimen; also compilations and limited-edition variations of the same release -- SO limited that some are pressed in runs of no more than five or ten copies!

That's not a misprint.

And yet, most of these rarities surprisingly do NOT sell for stupid prices on Discogs, and that says a lot, not only about The Heads' obscure status, but the unexceptional psych-rock they've produced over the years.

So, when I reviewed a CD called The Time is Now! in the All-Music Guide, I was really addressing a dozen ad-hoc products collected under one "roof," including 1998's Mao Tinitus EP, seen here in all of its day-glo cover art splendor and see-through orange wax.

Released by the venerable Man's Ruin label, this 10-inch found the four-headed monster of Simon Price (vocals, guitar), Paul Allen (guitar, keyboards), Hugo Morgan (bass), and Wayne Maskell (drums) tackling just to jams, but both exceed nine minutes in length.

The title track is first and it drags its baboon-butt forever, cycling through a lazy riff before some jazzy noodling and tectonic distortion blasts finally kick up the tempo behind acid rock guitar flailing and outer-space swooshes: half-Mudhoney, half-Monster Magnet.

But the reason I own this 10-inch is its incredible B-side, "Legevan Satellite," which launches into maybe the greatest hard rock riff ever concocted outside of late-'60s Detroit -- we're talking MC5-level dynamism and greatness here, people!

Alas, it too eventually resorts to extended, pulsing feedback, never to find its way back to a Motor City madhouse; and like most Heads numbers, vocals and lyrics seem to be purely incidental, captive passengers along for a ride with the music itself.

But the band still realized they'd stumbled on a winner, for once, and recorded a shorter (lamer) version for 2000's Everybody Knows We Got Nowhere LP, which only proved their inability to deliver focused and consistent material.

And that's why I once suggested that The Heads were the stoner rock equivalent of The Grateful Dead: unless your perception is chemically altered to begin with, you'll probably just be bored to tears.

p.s. -- In case you're wondering, that's a postcard overhead promoting a split release by Electric Wizard and Orange Goblin -- both of them far superior to The Heads, if you ask me.

Queens of the Stone Age: Queens of the Stone Age (1998)

Fans were still mourning stoner/desert rock iconoclasts Kyuss 25 years ago when three of its former members -- guitarist Josh Homme, bassist Nick Oliveri, and drummer Alfredo Hernndez -- became Queens of the Stone.

Queens of the what?

Actually, most of us diehards already knew the strange moniker from Kyuss' farewell EP, and I'd kept tabs on Homme's ensuing meanderings, which included touring with the Screaming Trees and leading the Palm Desert-based music collective known as the Desert Sessions.

It was out of that eclectic melting pot, mixing the stoner rock scene with musicians as diverse as Dean Ween, Alain Johannes, Chris Goss, Mark Lanegan, Les Claypool, Twiggy Ramirez, even P.J. Harvey, that Q.O.T.S.A.'s mutant sonic recipe got its unique flavor.

But, at first, I simply saw the Queens as a new breed of underground-doomed stoner rock when I picked up this self-titled CD at the specialized record store that once lurked in the basement of Chicago's historic Metro club.

How could I not, given the stylized, anti-commerce '70s erotica chosen for its cover by graphic artist (and future Man's Ruin label head) Frank Kozik? (*)

As I later described it in Loudwire, this was a "transitional record bridging the vast aesthetic gulf between Kyuss gale-force stoner metal and the Queens psychotic brand of art rock," adding that it "arrived to little fanfare in 1998 but reverberated far and wide."

Moreover, whereas future Q.O.T.S.A. LPs added loads of contributing musicians, this one was jammed into shape by the duo of Homme and Hernandez (Oliveri joined just in time to appear in the rear sleeve photo), and thus, it's a "guitar album" through-and-through.

Albeit one whose sheepish vocals, crunchy guitar, elastic bass, and metronomic drums felt simultaneously familiar and totally alien to stoner rock devotees, so I'll just share some of my personal, convoluted impressions of its songs ...

Beginning with an all-time favorite in "Regular John" (**), which, for a year or two, served as my Friday night, "get revved up to go out and break shit" music, with its relentless thrust and hypnotic, Motorik-like ur-riff ( Julian Cope).

Another mesmerizing standout, "Mexicola," rumbles down the bass' neck with a tone reminiscent of the Beastie Boys' "Sabotage," and leads a flock of slow-boiling siblings in "Walkin' On the Sidewalks," "You Would Know," and "You Can't Quit Me Baby."

As for stoner rock proper, the closest sounds here would be the bombastic power chords of "Avon" and labyrinthine contortions of "Hispanic Impressions," while the clearest glimpses of what lay ahead for Q.O.T.S.A. figured in the groovy "If Only," the shortwave radio distortion afflicting "How to Handle a Rope," and the sheer lunacy of "I Was a Teenage Hand Model."

This last song and another comically-titled highlight, "Give the Mule What He Wants," suggested listeners shouldn't take any of this too seriously, but we soon learned how seriously Homme saw things when he landed the major label and management backing to take Q.O.T.S.A. mainstream with 2000's fabulous Rated R.

Personally, I was thrilled for these Kyuss castaways, because I never expected a band this bizarre, let alone one with roots in the as-yet-unredeemed stoner rock scene, to sell millions of albums -- not least once my boys, Monster Magnet, had failed to do so with '98's No. 1 Active Rock hit "Space Lord."

But Queens of the Stone Age proved to be as unique a commercial/artistic phenomenon over the next few years as their peculiar moniker foreshadowed.

* Two different, N.S.F.W. images were used for the LP and CD: my original copy featured a crotch-shot of Trinidadian-British model Sylvia Bayo, but I'm afraid I haven't found a name for the young lady pictured on the vinyl.

** Co-written by former Monster Magnet/Wellwater Conspiracy guitarist John McBain.

Los Natas: Delmar (1998)

Though they would eventually mature into one of the world's most intriguing and distinctive stoner rock bands, Argentina's Los Natas were little more than Kyuss clones on their Man's Ruin debut album, Delmar.

I dunno, maybe those cactuses melting under the blazing desert sun tipped you off?

Sergio 'Ch.' Chotsourian (vocals, guitar), Miguel Fernandez (bass), and Walter Broide (drums, vocals) all hailed from Buenos Aires, and, starting in 1993, started finding common ground in their passion for '70s sounds and vintage musical equipment.

They were also initially named simply Natas, until being forced to add the Spanish article 'Los' when a naming rights conflict emerged with a Detroit-based gangsta/horrorcore rap group, but I'm pretty sure this worked out for the best ...

If nothing else, it gave Los Natas an added air of exoticism to help them stand out from all those other '90s stoner rock desert rats, though not until after this first effort, as the music quickly reveals.

This, as I said earlier, owed so much to Kyuss' admittedly brilliant, exploits of the early '90s, that it's simply impossible to praise songs like "Samurai," "1980," and "I Love You" on their own, unique merits.

There simply aren't any unique merits to be found!

But if I were to bet money on a game of Kyuss Karaoke, I'd still put it on Los Natas vs. fellow acolytes like Nebula, Mondo Generator, Wretch, etc., etc.

Sure, spacey, mellower instrumentals like "Trilogia," "Mux Cortoi," and "Alberto Migre" merely complete the disc's amazingly accurate Blues for the Red Sun impression, but at least they hint at the ways in which Los Natas would eventually achieve creative independence.

Said independence would gradually gain momentum on ensuing efforts like Ciudad de Brahman, the classic Corsario Negro, and via the experimental free rock and Indian music-inspired drones of the Toba Trance sets.

But arguably nothing was more important than Los Natas' decision to embrace their heritage and native tongue, which they did only a few times (see the title track and "El Negro") on the largely English-sung Delmar.

Therefore, I can only recommend this introductory LP to stoner rock completists and diehard Los Natas fans who may be working their way backwards from the band's more justifiably celebrated later works, but I'll still recommend it.

p.s. -- Originally released on cassette in 1996 (check out some images overhead, including custom cover art), Delmar was later reissued on CD and vinyl; my personal copy -- as brown as wet desert sand -- appears to date from 2018.

Sleep: The Sciences (2018)

Rarely have been so certain that Id slipped into a parallel dimension as when I attended the reunited Sleeps 2010 show at Brooklyns Masonic Temple and found myself surrounded, not by dazed-and-confused stoner rock and doom heshers like myself, but droves of young dudes sporting the most fashionable haircuts and manicured beards.

Or, as they are known by their taxonomical classification: Pitchforkus Hipsterus Intolerabilis.

All joking aside, the mind still boggles over Sleeps improbable shift of marketplace perspective: from perhaps the quintessential 90s stoner/doom proposition to a badge of underground credibility for the 21st Centurys hipster metal hordes.

Especially because the bands music didnt change, their audience did.

And yet, there was no denying this transition once vocalist/bassist Al Cisneros, guitarist Matt Pike, and guesting Neurosis drummer Jason Roeder (who stepped in for the retired Chris Hakius) signed with Jack Whites obnoxiously pretentious Third Man Records, which promptly scheduled The Sciences for release on April 20, 2018 -- a.k.a. Cannabis Culture Day.

So this is what cultural appropriation feels like!

Point being: all this left such a bad taste in my mouth that I waited nearly five years to invite The Sciences to join its fellow Sleep LPs on my turntable and vinyl racks, where it obviously fit right in, despite being such an obviously calculated nostalgic endeavor.

Emphasis on nostalgic because these songs add nothing to the Sleep sound (indeed, many date back to earlier writing sessions), but merely revive and recycle either the vintage, Sabbath-beholden stoned grooves of Holy Mountain or the sacred, leviathan doom of Jerusalem/Dopesmoker.

In the first category, we find the steamrolling Marijuanats Theme (visually rendered on the album cover) and the pun-tastic Giza Butler (complete with wah-wah bass intro), while, in the second, we get the rather fabulous Antarcticans Thawed (surely one of the funniest titles ever associated with global warming).

Another Dopesmoker-era outtake, Sonic Titan was first heard in live form on the 03 CD reissue, and all thats left beyond that are two instrumentals: the title track (little more than a power chord/volume-knob suspense-builder, but it works), and The Botanist, (a tasty baked jam eventually spitted and skewered by Pikes savage soloing).

I will say that the funny/punny song titles, lyrics (Giza Butler turns Dunes gom jabbar into bong jabbar, MuadDib into MuadDoob), and complete breakfast tableau depicted in the albums inner gatefold should remind offended first generation Sleep fans like myself not to take all this so seriously. (*)

So I wont, and I'll end this diatribe by saying that Ive made my peace with The Sciences (the music is all that matters, in the end), because of course Id rather hear MORE Sleep music than NO Sleep music at all, but that dont mean I wanna experience it with those trendy, late-arriving fans.

Now get off my lawn!

* Also, nice touch patterning the band photos in the insert after Rushs Moving Pictures.

Clutch: Sunrise on Slaughter Beach (2022)

Heres an interesting if altogether random pattern: it seems that Im especially partial to Clutch albums released at nine year intervals!

Count along with me: 2022s Sunrise on Slaughter Beach was the first LP by the stoner rock veterans to grab me by the throat (prompting the inevitable vinyl investment) since 13s Earth Rocker, and the same was true of 04s Blast Tyrant, and 95s self-titled sophomore opus, before that.

Go figure ...

Maybe it was the touring layoff enforced by Covid-19 (during which Clutch even tried their hands at some virtual shows!) that afforded Neil Fallon (vocals, rhythm guitar), Tim Sult (lead guitar), Dan Maines (bass), and Jean-Paul Gaster (drums) more time to perfect these songs before entering Baltimore, MDs Magpie Cage Studio with producer Tom Dalgety (Pixies, Ghost, The Cult, etc.).

And while Earth Rocker largely focused on heavy, speedy fare inspired by the groups touring with Motrhead, Sunrise on Slaughter Beach is, dare I say, one of the bands most well-rounded efforts, covering most of the sounds the group has shifted (get it?) into over the course of their -- wow! -- 30-year career.

The resulting nine songs only amount to a trim, tidy 33 minutes of expertly seasoned hard rock, stoner rock, space rock, groove rock, punk rock, metal, etc., but theres so much meat on their musical bones, topped by that special sauce: Fallons imaginative lyrics, some of the best in the business.

These cater to nerds and hobbyists of all ages thanks to inspirational touchstones like Blade Runner (raging opener Red Alert (Boss Metal Zone)), Dungeons and Dragons (Mountain of Bone), and terrifying outer space exploits (Skeletons on Mars, theremin included) worthy of Ray Bradbury.

But this aint no boys club, thanks to the captivating female protagonists of Nosferatu Madre (which places an undead avenger on the Mayflower and Plymouth Rock) and Mercy Brown (which revives the legend of a Rhode Island vampire but is built like a Mother Goose rhyme).

And real world scenarios also make the cut, even if elliptically, when Slaughter Beach trips out on economic inequality, Jackhammer Our Names ponders mankinds cyclical fate (from making history, to becoming history), and Three Golden Horns celebrates jazz icon Rahsaan Roland Kirk (you GOTTA watch the video) in amusing fashion.

But the albums biggest treasure is We Strive for Excellence, which I mistook for some kind of proletariat manifesto until Fallon explained that the song looks back fondly on childhood summers filled with grand plans gone awry, inexplicable bruises, untreated injuries, and, of course, the timeless wisdom of Evel Knievel.

I have a hammer, a box of nails; Two M80s and punk sticks; My uncle's favorite Farrah Fawcett lighter; A Schwinn hurricane with BMX grips; We deliver where Knievel failed; What's a little bit of tetanus? Pledge allegiance to the denim flag; And strive for excellence!

I found at least a dozen two by fours; Marine grade plywood; No six million-dollar men; No retakes, no Hollywood; One and done, feet off the pedals; Naive elegance; Salute the denim, light the pyro; And strive for excellence!

You're in the Cub Scouts, right? I believe I need a tourniquet; I can hear my mama calling; Hand over that snake bite kit; We deliver where Knievel failed; What's a little bit of tetanus? Pledge allegiance to the denim flag; And strive for excellence!

Yes we do! We strive for excellence! Yes we do! The dinner bell aint calling me home!

If this song doesnt get your motor running, your transmission is just plain broken!

And its albums this good that snap nonsensical nine-year cycles, and make me wonder why I dont feel so drawn to everything in Clutchs discography ... but thats the way it goes.

Salute the denim!

More Clutch: Blast Tyrant, Earth Rocker.

The Obsessed: The Obsessed (1990) [Recorded 1985]

Years before the heavy metal community became obsessed with journeyman Scott Wino Weinrich, he was just about the only person obsessed with The Obsessed (maybe not even he), when this eponymous LP recorded in 1985 was unearthed and released by Hellhound Records, five years later.

At the time, Wino was the frontman of West Coast doom dinosaurs Saint Vitus, whom hed joined in 86 and then contributed to three studio albums (Born too Late, Mournful Cries, and V) that assured the bands underground credentials, but didnt exactly translate into widespread fame and fortune.

Consider, too, the long and winding road Wino had traveled since 1976, when he formed a band named Warhorse in Potomac, MD, later becoming the Leather Nunz (now theres a clever name), and finally The Obsessed, while cutting their teeth on a mixture of metal, hard rock, and punk.

In the spring of 83, the group issued the Sodden Jackal EP and notched one of its tracks, Concrete Cancer, on Metal Blades Metal Massacre VI compilation, prompting the recording of this self-titled full-length, only for it to be shelved when Wino joined Vitus.

But the music documented by Wino, bassist Mark Laue, and drummer Ed Gulli obviously survived, gathering proverbial dust and cobwebs that ultimately suited authentic and majestic doom revivals like Tombstone Highway, Forever Midnight, and Ground Out all too well.

Especially when these were countered with select adrenal bursts of hard rock (Freedom) and punk (Inner Turmoil), a few subtle psychedelic flourishes (River of Soul), and Winos slashing solos, which ripped through all and sundry like a hot knife through metallic molasses.

Alas, the commercial musical climate was no more favorable to The Obsessed in 1990 than it would have been in 85, but since Vitus career was obviously treading water, the time was ripe for Wino to close that chapter of his career and start a new one with his old band.

And so, after recruiting bassist Scott Reeder (later of Kyuss, Unida, etc.) and drummer Greg Rogers (later of Goatsnake), The Obsessed were reborn, and soon got to work on their second and -- in my opinion -- best LP in 1992s Lunar Womb, inching Wino that much closer to broad metal fan obsession.

Uh, always within reason, but you know what I mean ...

Masters of Reality: Sunrise on the Sufferbus (1992)

Im not too arrogant to admit that Masters of Realitys sophomore set, Sunrise on the Sufferbus, went waaaaaay over my head 30 years ago.

At the time, I was still a musically inexperienced devil child, weaned on a steady diet of AC/DC, Iron Maiden, and Metallica, and therefore ill-equipped to comprehend the albums eclectic sounds and eccentric words ... but I got better!

Well, more knowledgeable, anyway, and now I can only marvel at this irreverent collection of classic rock with benefits from the minds of two retro-rock nobodies (basically) and one of the most famous (and infamous) musicians of our time.

How a pair of balding, overweight musicians from Syracuse, New York like vocalist/guitarist Chris Goss and bassist Googe (one more letter and he could have been rich!) convinced a living legend like Ginger Baker -- Creams controversial and irascible time-keeper -- to join their ranks, Ill never know.

But they did, and so Goss dutifully raised his game to deliver an impressively varied set -- at times playfully libidinous (She Got Me (When She Got Her Dress On)), at others innocently enamored (Jody Sings), and, at others still, ready for a seance (J.B. Witchdance).

And those are just the first three songs!

As the album unfolds, ever-driven by Gingers authoritative shuffling and swinging, Goss brings a fragile croon to Rolling Green, a sinister menace to V.H.V., a friendly lullaby in The Moon in Your Pocket, and finally cant resist a blatant Cream tribute called Gimme Water.

Theres also a dada-like randomness (later to resurface in Goss productions for Queens of the Stone Age) to humorous vignettes like Bicycle, Rabbit One, and Madonna, while on T.U.S.A. the fearsome Mr. Baker politely but firmly corrects Americans on the proper way of making tea:

They bring you a cup with a lemon slice; And an unopened tea bag beside it (how nice); And a pot of water and it may be hot; But boiling it isnt so tea you have not. Its boiling water that brings out teas flavor; With a dash of milk, youve a real brew to savor; They drink lukewarm water that looks like gnat pee; And it's got nothing to do with a good cup of tea.

Indeed, and Ill close with two of my favorites: the rambunctious Tilt-a-Whirl and the cinematic 100 Years (Of Tears On the Wind), where sweeping strings evoke images of a Spaghetti Western that would make Sergio Leone and Ennio Morricone (maybe also Felix Pappalardi) proud.

One heck of an album, Sunrise on the Sufferbus, obviously ages like a good wine (we listeners can only hope to do the same) and its too bad it proved to be an impossible act to follow for Masters of Reality, especially once Ginger stormed off towards new misadventures.

More Masters of Reality: Masters of Reality.

Corrosion of Conformity: Deliverance (1994)

For such a solid album, Corrosion of Conformitys Deliverance sure felt anticlimactic to me, but thats because Im a self-avowed nut for its 1991 predecessor, Blind, and its combustible amalgam of politicized punk, hardcore, and metal.

Deliverance, by comparison, simply couldnt match that excitement, though I had no real problem with C.O.C.s latest career reboot, which saw the ouster of singer Karl Agell (great pipes!) and bassist Phil Swisher (who?), the return of founding bassist Mike Dean, and Pepper Keenans usurpation (well, he did!) of the role of frontman and driving force.

With Pepper at the helm, C.O.C. essentially said so long! to their crossover past (except for the punky My Grain) and dragged Black Sabbath with them south of the Mason-Dixon, while sneaking a low-key grunge conformity (couldnt resist) into the mix, for good measure (and added record sales).

All that being said, Heavens Not Overflowing boasted one of the 1990s absolute greatest heavy metal riffs, bar none, first single Albatross overcame far less interesting, doom-laden power chords to charge the MTV and radio airwaves, and second single Clean My Wounds soon followed with its choppy, catchy staccatos.

Thats three winners right out of the gate -- a veritable bounty by the periods deplorable standards for CD filler -- though C.O.C. also resorted to some of their own with Shake Like You, Shelter, and throwaway instrumental intros like Without Wings, Mano de Mono, and #2121313.

Luckily, Deliverance also offered some secondary standouts in the grinding Broken Man, the swinging Seor Limpio, and the harmonic, monolithic Seven Days, before stalling on the repetitive, vaguely psychedelic, Mike Dean-sung title track and a final slog too many in Pearls Before Swine.

And still good fortune smiled upon the band and producer John Custer when Sonys Columbia Records purchased their indie label, Relativity (on the same day as Kurt Cobain died, according to Dean in this reissues liner notes), and funded Deliverances completion, after almost a year of toil.

Alas, that major label muscle could only take the album within shouting distance of a Gold certification, after which C.O.C. was rudely dropped due to the weaker sales of '96s Wiseblood, and, thus, went from Deliverance to re-delivery to the indie ranks within a few short years.

More Corrosion of Conformity: Animosity, Blind, Wiseblood.

Spiritu: Spiritu (2002)

Long before Albuquerque, New Mexico, became synonymous with illicit drugs via the award-wining series, Breaking Bad, it was coincidentally (?) home to one of the preeminent stoner rock labels, MeteorCity, whose artists included Nebula, Unida, Spirit Caravan, and the lesser-known Spiritu.

(Breaking Bad and 90s stoner rock also had the desert in common, so the coincidences keep piling up!)

Formed by MeteorCity founder and, on this occasion, vocalist Jadd Schickler, guitarist Mike Chav Chavez, bassist John Bess, and drummer James (yes, ... just James), Spiritu headed to Seattle in late 2001 to work with renowned indie rock producer Jack Endino (Nirvana, Mudhoney, etc.).

As the story goes, it took only three days to record this self-titled first (and last) album, which I was only too happy to review for the All-Music Guide when Jadd shipped me a promo copy, before Spiritu headed out for a European tour in support of Clutch and Spiritual Beggars.

And while Ill admit that I indulged in the odd spot of hyperbole on behalf of my friend, I can honestly say, listening back 20 years later, that Spiritu had a lot going for them -- both in terms of covering the stoner rock ground rules and exploring some neighboring music genres.

To wit: nine-minute opener Z (Noonday Demon) harbored alien textures reminiscent of Australian space/prog weirdos Alchemist, the similarly epic Glorywhore dangled its long alt/psych tendrils into Alice in Chains pool, and the percussively slammed Slump was the albums third and final nine-minute offering.

Perhaps there was some numerology at play here?

There was certainly something bizarre, exotic, or at the very least tongue-in-cheek afoot, because after showcasing Bees expert bass playing on the unusually concise Clean Livin (which could have slotted comfortably into a Slo Burn or Lowrider LP), the otherwise textbook stoned rocker Fat Man in Thailand amusingly quoted lyrics from Murray Heads 1980s curiosity, One Night in Bangkok.

No, seriously!

Finally, Im relatively sure Spiritus cover of the old Sir Lord Baltimore nugget Woman Tamer was my very first exposure to this underground proto-metal classic, at a time when S.L.B.s cult discography was still quite elusive, pre-Internet-facilitated rediscovery.

In sum: while they obviously didnt enjoy the same popularity as Breaking Bad -- either in their day or in re-runs -- Spiritu left a pretty good-looking corpse in this LP.

Except for an additional four tracks issued in 06 as the Human Failures split release with fellow MeteorCity signings Village of Dead Roads, Spiritu were heard from no more, and the label, too, bid a three-CD farewell via 07s ... And Back to Earth Again box set.

Los Natas: Corsario Negro (2002)

I must own a LOT of stoner rock albums because, once again, I had a perfect candidate lined up for April 20th without even trying or advance planning!

And this has to be one of my favorites first sentences for an All-Music Guide review, if I do say so myself: What has six legs, three heads, sings in Spanish, and sounds like a herd of dinosaurs marching across a pre-historic Patagonian beach?

Why, it must be Argentina's phenomenal Los Natas, whose earth-shaking brand of doom and stoner metal on 2002s Corsario Negro still ranks among the finest of its kind released this side of the year 2000 (shout out to Small Stone Records), all of 20 years later.

So good it transcended the minuscule but maniacal stoner rock fan-base to seduce straights and hipsters alike, Corsario Negro was also the album where Los Natas finally transcended the colossal creative debt to Kyuss that tainted first and second albums, Delmar and Ciudad de Brahmam.

Recorded at Buenos Aires Abasto Studios with the aid of American producer Billy Anderson (Sleep, Clutch, Neurosis, Fu Manchu, etc.), the album managed to instill a unique sensibility and oddly majestic atmosphere into the usual 90s stoner/doom/space/psych/trance/sludge ingredients.

Opening with the amusing 2002 (essentially the Zarathustra theme from 2001: A Space Odyssey gone doom), the album rumbles into gear with three astonishing distillations of all of the above in the mesmerizing Planeta Solitario, the galloping Patas de Elefante, and the all-time classic El Cono del Encono.

The albums largely instrumental second half cant quite match the amazing first (see also Lei Motive) but it does make it possible for the bands folksy (Hey Jimmy, El Gauchito), blues, jazz and jammy undertones to shine through further highlights like Bumburi and the avalanche of a title track.

Bottom line: Corsario Negros expanded sonic arsenal and newfound mastery of dynamic swings, tension and release, saw Los Natas reaching a new stage in their evolution and opening the door to deeper experiments in droning doom and Indian classical music on the Toba Trance tandem of 2003 and 04.

By contrast, subsequent releases like El Hombre Montaa (2006) and Nuevo Orden de la Libertad (2009) found Los Natas focused on still compelling, if slightly less adventurous forms of post-stoner hard rock and heavy blues.

Both creative avenues are full of stellar songs and striking moments, well worth investigating, yet their almost bi-polar schism enhances my belief that Corsario Negro was Los Natas signature album, and a career masterpiece these Argentinians can be proud of, should they never choose to reform.

p.s. -- Some of these words were borrowed and then greatly evolved from my All-Music Guide review of Los Natas Corsario Negro.
